[[tabview]]
[[tab DELETIONS (OVERVIEW)]]
@@ @@
[[div class="space large orange"]]

This is the hub for the Department of Deletions, an esoteric arm of the Foundation that acts both as a branch of the Organization and as a GOI with its own directives and ulterior motives. Deletions shares similarities with other abstract departments, such as the [https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/departments#surrealistics-dept DEPARTMENT OF SURREALISTICS], the [https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/unreality-hub DEPARTMENT OF UNREALITY], and the [https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/scp-6511 DEPARTMENT OF ONE]. However, the Department of Deletions is functionally distinct from all of these, occupying a unique perspective, dealing with bizarre anomalies in forms of existence both familiar yet unrecognizable, absurd yet logical, allegorical yet prosaic, elegiac yet self-indulgent.  

Deletions operates out of Research Station Mnemosyne, where it employs a gestalt consciousness created from bits and pieces of beings originating from deleted narratives that still exist in memory. These pieces persist in an inactive state until they are overwritten, coalescing in response to anomalies that impact the status of the Database or its contents. 

Members of the department are burdened by the nature and awareness of their own existence. Being made of multiple fractions of deleted individuals, they are fundamentally unstable when assuming a physical form. They "fall apart", both physically and mentally, when exposed to time. Thus, Deletions agents tend to avoid interacting with timelines unless absolutely necessary, which it often is. 

Once the relevant Database issue is addressed, Research Station Mnemosyne and all Deletions agents assigned to the anomaly return to dormancy with the hope of being completely overwritten before the next issue arises. 

Articles featuring Deletions have a distinct, computer science-oriented framing, with heavy surrealism and themes of repetition, loss of individuality/diffusion of personality, existential dread, slow annihilation, eternity/deep time, wiki/societal metacommentary, and the destruction of preexisting notions/paradigms. See [[span class="bd"]]ADDITIONAL INFORMATION[[/span]] for further elaboration on Deletions' perspective. 
[[/div]]
@@ @@
[[/tab]]
[[tab ADDITIONAL INFORMATION]]
@@ @@
[[div class="space large orange"]]

As the name suggests, Deletions is a department comprised of data fragments once belonging to content that has since been deleted from Wikidot's database directory. Contrary to the layperson's understanding, deletion does not entirely remove this content from storage. 

The nature of persistent memory is accomplished with four basic operations (//create, read, update, delete//), three user attributes (//read, write, execute//), and the relationship between the two. In so many words, the Database is managed with the //creation// of data in allocated space, the //reading// of data in that space, the //updating// of said data, and the process of //deletion//, which marks previously-allocated space as free to be overwritten by other data. On the other hand, every Wikidot user possesses varying levels of three relevant types of permission: //reading// existing information, //writing// new information to storage, and //executing// functions to enter the directory and locate/manipulate information after it has been written.

Database content is comprised of //reference data// written to various sectors of memoryspace, the //file objects// that act as identifiers or containers for that data, and the //pointers// that indicate the location of the former when accessing the latter. Deletion severs these connections by erasing identifiers, leaving the values and behaviors described by those identifiers untouched--a process also known as abstraction. The old data then remains on the file system until new data comes along and overwrites it. This is why data recovery agents can occasionally restore deleted/corrupted files from damaged, wiped, or faulty hard drives. 
[[include :scp-wiki:component:image-features-source |click-fullscreen=--]
|speed=Number 
|float=true
|align=right
|width=300px
|url=https://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/deleted/DATAB.png
|alt=alt|alt-text=The Database
|add-caption=true/false
|caption=Database sectors from the perspective of Deletions. Click to enlarge.
]]
Sometimes, a file's allocated space becomes overwritable, but the information written to that region next only fills it partially. Since data is typically written in contiguous blocks called //chunks//, the portions of free space containing junk information may exist long after their original deletion.

This junk information is the materia by which Deletions agents are formed.

When not interacting with a timeline, the Database is experienced in a temporally-isolated substrate acting as a physical representation of digital space. In this mode of existence, it becomes clear that timelines exist which are built upon vastly different frameworks.[[footnote]]Including models that do not currently exist, or those that directly contradict other models.[[/footnote]] Thus, the average Deletions agent is aware of the phenomena described by the phrase "there is no canon". They are also acutely aware of the questionable nature of truth on a given day, as well as their inherent "fictionality". View the [[span class="bd"]]GLOSSARY OF TERMS[[/span]] for more on the included graphic.

[[/div]] 
